The command prompt is where you type commands in Linux. It appears when you open a Terminal.

A typical Linux command prompt looks like this:

<user_name>@<hostname><symbol>:

Here,
Username:  name of logged-in user
Hostname: host name/computer name
Symbol: user type

$= Normal user
#= Root user

Mayur@ubuntu:~$

What it tells you:

mayur → Username

@ubuntu → System/Hostname

~ → Home directory (~ = home directory)

$ → Normal user prompt

# → Root user prompt

Purpose:

Allows users to execute commands
Interact with the system
Control files, directories, processes, etc.

Decoding the Structure of the Command Prompt

Let’s break the prompt:

[username]@[hostname]:[current_path][symbol]

Effective Command Prompt Usage: 



Sudo su -                          Switch User(Superuser DO)

Sudo -I allow a user with proper permission to execute a command such as root user

Man man                        Manual [ To Open manual, for quit use 'q']

mkdir                               Create Folder/directory

mkdir -p                          Nested Directory

Rmdir                               remove Directory

ls                                       List files

Pwd                                  View where you are

cd /path/to/directory  Move between directories

touch file1.txt                Create files:

nano file1.txt                 Edit files:

cat file1.txt                     View file contents:

rm file1.txt
rm -r foldername          Remove files or folders: [ recursively means that the command will operates on directory and all of subdirectory and files
 
History                            Shows command history.
	
 Getting Started with the Linux Terminal

Opening the terminal:
Ubuntu: Ctrl + Alt + T
CentOS/RHEL: Applications → System Tools → Terminal
Mac: Applications → Utilities → Terminal
Windows (WSL): Ubuntu app
Important Terminal Concepts:

Case sensitive
File.txt and file.txt are different.

Safe practices:

Be careful with rm -rf — dangerous.
Use sudo only when necessary.

